cd /      => To go into the particular directory
pwd       => print working directory
mkdir     => To create a new directory(creating the folder)
touch     => To create a new file 
cp        => Copy file
mv        => Move/rename file
rm        => Delete a file
cat       => View a file
chmod     => To give permission 


ls command
   ls        => Gives list files and directories in the current directory.
   ls -l    => shows detailed information 
      (-rw-r--r-- 1 ec2-user ec2-user 0 Mar 6 10:20 test.txt)
      | Column       | Meaning          |
      | ------------ | ---------------- |
      | `-rw-r--r--` | File permissions |
      | `1`          | Number of links  |
      | `ec2-user`   | Owner            |
      | `ec2-user`   | Group            |
      | `0`          | File size        |
      | `Mar 6`      | Date             |
      | `test.txt`   | File name        |

   ls - a   => shows hidden files
   ls -la   => detailed view + hidden files
   ls /<home> => gives the list in the given directory
   ls -lh   => shows detailed view in human readable form
   ls -lah  => shows everything clearly

/ => Gives Top most directory OS vs ~ => Give the Top most directory of the current user

cd command
   cd        => Changing directory
   cd ..     => Go one diectory back
   cd -      => Goes to previous directory
   cd ~      => Goes to home directory of the specific user
   cd /      => Goes to root directory of the OS
   cd /home/ => Goes to specific directory inside the directory
   cd ../..  => Go back two directories
   cd ~<user_name> => Goes to the given user

mkdir command
   mkdir<dir_name> => Creates the directory
   mkdir project1 project2 => Can create multiple directories
   mkdir /home/ec2-user/<dir_name>  => Creates in the specific location
   
touch command
   touch file.txt => Creates the file
   touch touch app.log server.txt nginx.log  => Can create multiple file 
   touch /home/ec2-user/test.txt  => Can create file in particular dir 


READ & WRITE FILE
-----------------

(cat-to read, echo-to write)

echo "<Text>" > <file_name>.txt   => Writes inside the file (>) This overrides the existing text inside the given file 

echo "<Text>" >> <file_name>.txt   => Writes inside the file (>) This append the existing text inside the given file 

EG : echo "DevOps learning" > file1.txt
     echo "Linux commands practice" >> file1.txt 
   
    
cat <file_name>.txt           => This show the content inside the file


To WRITE LARGE TEXT:- nano or vi

 Vi command (creates file and open editor, if file is present only opens editor)
    vi <file_name>.txt - This opens the vi editor 
    | Command | Purpose             |
    | ------- | ------------------- |
    | `i`     | Insert text         |
    | `ESC`   | Exit insert mode    |
    | `:w`    | Save                |
    | `:q`    | Quit                |
    | `:wq`   | Save & quit         |
    | `:q!`   | Quit without saving |

nano command (creates file and open editor, if file is present only opens editor )

    nano <file_name>.txt - This opens nano editor
    | Shortcut | Function    |
    | -------- | ----------- |
    | CTRL + O | Save file   |
    | CTRL + X | Exit editor |
    | CTRL + K | Cut line    |
    | CTRL + U | Paste line  |
    | CTRL + W | Search text |
    | CTRL + G | Help        |


mv command (Used to move files/directories or rename them)
   
   mv <file1.txt> <file2.txt> => move file1 content to file2 
   mv <dir1> <dir2>           => move content in dir 1 to dir 2

   EG :- mv config.txt config_backup.txt

rm command (Deletes the file and directory) 
   //files usually cannot be recovered.

   rm <filename>               => deletes the file 
   rm <file1> <file2>          => Can also delete multiple files
   rm -r <directory_name>      => To delete directory
   rm -i <file.txt>            => Safer asks before deleting
   rm -f <file_name>           => Force delete